More than 1,000 Federal personnel are on the ground in Maui to aid response efforts for the wildfires. President Biden and First Lady Jill Biden visited Maui and saw the destruction caused by the wildfires. The President has committed to delivering everything the people of Hawaiʻi need and his Administration will be there for as long as it takes. FEMA Region 9 Administrator Bob Fenton has been appointed as the Chief Federal Response Coordinator for Maui. Thousands of personnel from various Federal departments and agencies are working with state and local partners to assess ongoing needs and provide resources and personnel. The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) has allocated $1.3 million through the Rapid Unsheltered Survivor Housing program to help communities on Maui affected by the wildfires. The Administration encourages impacted individuals to register for Federal assistance at www.disasterassistance.gov or by calling 1-800-621-3362. FEMA has multiple language translations available. A joint Disaster Recovery Center has been opened at the University of Hawaiʻi Maui College. The Small Business Administration is conducting outreach to businesses in Maui County for the Economic Injury Disaster Loan program. HUD is providing relief from foreclosures of Federal Housing Administration-insured mortgages and home equity conversion mortgages. HUD has also released regulatory and administrative waivers to help communities accelerate their recovery, including funding for housing rehabilitation and reconstruction, infrastructure improvements, and assistance to people at risk of homelessness.